nly way to boot the cloud server is to login into the control panel and click the button to boot, this means the process can\'t be fully scripted. Unless a way to automate the booting and sleeping of the cloud server can be found the syncing will have to be a partially manual process which means it can only happen during the day or evening.\r\n\r\nThe cloud server is charged for by the hour and is free when sleeping if put to sleep using a particular option in the control panel. A normal shutdown (sudo shutdown -h now) will not put the server into sleep mode and you will have to pay for the Harddrive space.\r\n\r\nSome notes I made after the initial discussion:\r\nProcesses will be needed to automate database syncing, file syncing, etc, also to automate restore when moving back to main server.\r\n\r\nWould need backup subdomains of all urls, and matching SSL certificates.\r\nThese would always point to the backup server.\r\nThe backup server would be in maintenance mode with all urls pointing to a page saying something like \"The backup server is currently not in use please use the main url\". This is to prevent users being confused and updating the backup server when the live server is running.\r\n\r\nMoodle data would need to be updated to use the backup url where embedded in database.\r\n\r\nFailover process would be to boot backup server.\r\nRestore latest data available if neccessary.\r\nTake the server out of maintenance mode, which would enable all the website urls and start the background processes.\r\nThen to tell clients to use backup urls. some data maybe lost depending on frequency of syncing.\r\n\r\n\r\nRestore process.\r\nOnce main server is fixed, it is put into maintenace mode using puppet. This stops uses updating stale data.\r\n\r\nAn offpeak time to be agreed to restore.\r\n\r\nAt that time put backup server into maintenance mode (to stop data being updated).\r\nDo data dump and restore it to main server.\r\nsync updated files from backup server to main server.\r\n\r\nTake main server out of maintenance mode.\r\n\r\nPut backup server to sleep until next sync time.\r\nTell clients to use normal urls.\r\n\r\n1and1 dynamic cloud server.\r\nSleep Mode allows you to save your data for up to 6 months for free\r\n2 cores, 6GB RAM, 200GB HDD Ubuntu 12.04 LTS\r\n£0.10p per hour, £72 per month(30 days) excluding VAT.\r\nWe can probably save some money by only having 2GB RAM most of the time and just increasing it before booting it during the failover process.\r\n\r\nThese were just my initial thoughts after the first discussion, I will need to think about it more before giving a final solution.','2014-10-31 15:36:27',0),(7549,1328,'Issue',6,'Change 2 page 7 item 2.5\r\nIf CLaSic team OTLA grade refers to In-House OTLA grade, what is the difference between columns 3 and 4 on the PDF.\r\n\r\nOther than that looks good.','2014-10-31 16:51:11',0),(7550,1334,'Issue',6,'Released to live','2014-10-31 20:34:46',0),(7551,1334,'Issue',6,'','2014-10-31 20:42:52',0),(7552,1328,'Issue',3,'0.0.3 released. Please re-proof','2014-11-03 14:37:16',0),(7553,959,'Issue',3,NULL,'2014-11-03 16:32:32',0),(7554,1092,'Issue',3,NULL,'2014-11-03 16:43:44',0),(7555,1166,'Issue',3,NULL,'2014-11-03 16:44:34',0),(7556,1176,'Issue',3,NULL,'2014-11-03 16:44:48',0),(7557,1183,'Issue',3,NULL,'2014-11-03 16:45:10',0),(7558,1191,'Issue',3,NULL,'2014-11-03 16:46:02',0),(7559,1192,'Issue',3,NULL,'2014-11-03 16:46:25',0),(7560,1328,'Issue',6,'Looks good.','2014-11-03 19:49:36',0),(7561,1332,'Issue',6,'Page 18 item ii\r\n\r\n\"Provides definitive records of providers all the whole provision\"\r\nJust sounds totally wrong what does \"all the whole provision\" mean.\r\n\r\nPage 22 point 9 and 10\r\nThe provider action report will show the new criteria dialog (when I get chance to implement it) so I think these points are a little out of date.\r\n\r\nPage 27 point 10 the Quick Filter\r\nparagraph 1 and 3\r\nThe example you give of Provider TLO Grade will be out